"store_listing" = "Baby-Safe Home AR is an app that helps you make your home a safer place for your baby in a fun and innovative way by using elements of „Augmented Reality (AR)“. Use your camera to detect objects in your home, and if the objects could be a possible danger for your toddler, Baby-Safe Home AR will notify and show you how you can avoid accidents! Keep track of what you have to take care of in a checklist and get additional, regular safety tips and advice!\n\n*Features*\n- Use your camera to detect dangers: With the camera view you can point your cellphone at different objects in your home. Baby-Safe Home AR will inform you about possible dangers for your little one and how you can avoid accidents.\n- Use the checklist to mark dangers as banned: Once you have detected possible dangers for your baby with the camera, the danger is automatically added to your checklist. Once you have banned the possible danger from your house, you can mark the entries as checked! \n- Get daily tips, infos and recommendations: Get tips and further recommendations how to make your home a safer place for your baby!\n\n*How it works*\nOpen the camera in Baby-Safe Home AR to use our object detection functionalities. Point the camera at different objects in your home. Make sure to cover single, full objects on the screen. If the object could cause accidents or be a possible danger for your little one, Babysafe will notify you and give you advice how to avoid possible accidents.\n\n\n*Disclaimer*\nBaby-Safe Home AR can give you advice and raise awareness for the safety of your baby. Even though you might have marked all dangers discovered by the app as banned, we cannot guarantee that nothing will happen. Watch out, every home has individual dangers for the little ones and it is your responsibility to make your home a safe place for your baby!\n\n\n*FAQs*\nHow does that whole thing work?\nBaby-Safe Home AR uses the MLKit library by Google to detect objects. In the background there is an object detection model, that defines a list of classifications for detected objects. Baby-Safe Home AR uses this technology to detect and classify objects in your home and gives you relevant information about how to avoid accidents with babies for the given objects.\n\nIs my data sent to any server?\nNO. Your images or anything that is detected in your home stay on your device, no personalised or generated data is sent to any server or other location. As stated before Baby-Safe Home AR uses the MLKit library by Google. Google might send hardware-information, usage data and statistics to their servers, but this data does not contain any personal data or images of your home.\nBaby-Safe Home AR also works offline without an internet connection.\n\nWhy doesn’t the app recognise certain objects?\nObject detection and image classification is a research field that is constantly improved. Baby-Safe Home AR is using a state of the art object detection and image classification library and model. However, objects come in different shapes and variations – not all objects might be recognised. Also light conditions and camera quality can have an impact on the recognition process.";
"menu_main_bottombar_wishlist" = "Create a baby registry";





/* DANGERS */
"danger_power_title" = "Installing socket fuses";
"danger_power_text" = "Baby and child fingers fit exactly into the holes of a socket. Therefore, there is a particular risk of fatal electric shock. Using socket protectors can prevent this. Little crawlers are sure to immediately find the unsecured sockets in your home.";
"danger_toiletwater_title" = "Close toilet seat";
"danger_toiletwater_text" = "Children can drown in very shallow water and colourful toilet blocks encourage toddlers to try them. You can prevent both with a toilet lid safety device, so %1$s can neither fall in nor eat the poisonous toilet stone.";
"danger_furniture_tipover_title" = "Attach anti-tilt device for furniture";
"danger_furniture_tipover_text" = "When little ones become mobile, they try to hold on to everything and climb up. Furniture can tip over and fall on %1$s as a result. An anti-tip device for furniture can prevent the worst from happening. Large appliances, such as a TV, could also tip over and fall onto %1$s. Try to secure them with the help of the anti-tip device as well.";
"danger_furniture_fallingof_title" = "Remove tablecloths";
"danger_furniture_fallingof_text" = "During their first attempts at walking, %1$s will hold on to anything that is not nailed down. Tablecloths in particular are very dangerous, as the little ones can not only injure themselves on the falling objects, but can also scald themselves with hot soup, for example. Therefore, do not use tablecloths and check which objects could hurt %1$s when falling down.";
"danger_furniture_edges_title" = "Protect corners and edges";
"danger_furniture_edges_text" = "The little monkeys can hit their heads on corners and edges when learning to walk or when playing. To prevent injuries, use a corner and/or edge protector.";
"danger_furniture_drawer_title" = "Lock drawers";
"danger_furniture_drawer_text" = "Drawers can bring several dangers at once: on the one hand they are a climbing aid for %1$s, but also intriguing and dangerous. Small children's fingers can quickly become trapped in the drawer. That hurts! A smart remedy is the use of magnetic locks.";
"danger_plant_poison_title" = "Remove poisonous plants";
"danger_plant_poison_text" = "Some plants are poisonous. Fruits, leaves and flowers can cause poisoning if eaten. Other plants secrete liquid, which can be dangerous to %1$s. If you are unsure, consult a plant guide, ask at your local nursery, or use your own plant identification apps. The safest thing to do is to remove the plants.";
"danger_plant_sting_title" = "Keep prickly plants out of reach";
"danger_plant_sting_text" = "Some plants have thorns or spines. To prevent the little munchkins from pricking their fingers, it is best to place them out of reach of %1$s.";
"danger_plant_soil_title" = "Make plant soil inaccessible";
"danger_plant_soil_text" = "Potting soil or granules usually contain fertilizers and are therefore harmful to %1$s. Stretch a plant protection net over the pot and the soil and protect small plant explorers from poisoning.";
"danger_washingmachine_title" = "Lock washing machine";
"danger_washingmachine_text" = "The washing machine or clothes dryer are often used by children as a hiding place. It is especially dangerous when the door locks %1$s inside. With a universal lock, the door remains closed and does not provide a hiding place.";
"danger_radiator_title" = "Protect hot radiators";
"danger_radiator_text" = "Attention, hot! Radiators and pipes become very hot and can cause burns. Pipes could be insulated. You could also make the radiator inaccessible for %1$s.";
"danger_lightbulb_title" = "Eliminate hot light fixtures";
"danger_lightbulb_text" = "Conventional light bulbs or halogen lamps get hot. Protect your child's fingers and do something good for the environment: LED lamps do not get hot and are also energy-saving.";
"danger_door_pinch_title" = "Prevent jamming at door";
"danger_door_pinch_text" = "Trapped fingers in doors are one of the most common injuries. You can use a foam doorstop to prevent %1$s from getting their fingers caught in the door. Be careful not to use heavy door stops for the floor, as little ones could get hurt with them. The foam doorstops are specially designed for children.";
"danger_door_pinchback_title" = "Preventing pinching on door hinges";
"danger_door_pinchback_text" = "There is also a risk of pinching little children's fingers on the hinge of a door. A pinch guard can reduce this risk.";
"danger_door_lockout_title" = "Securely lock front door";
"danger_door_lockout_text" = "Especially in the case of front doors, there is also the danger that the toddlers lock themselves out unnoticed. A door lock can prevent %1$s from opening the door.";
"danger_window_title" = "Prevent window fall";
"danger_window_text" = "Falls from the window are life-threatening. You can prevent this with window and balcony door safety devices. Also make sure that the little ones cannot crawl onto the windowsill.";
"danger_stairs_title" = "Prevent fall on stairs";
"danger_stairs_text" = "When the little world explorers become mobile, they are magically attracted to stairs. To prevent %1$s falling down the stairs, a stair gate can help remove this danger. It can also help to keep the little ones away from other dangers.";
"danger_hotwater_title" = "Avoid scalding by hot water";
"danger_hotwater_text" = "Hot water can cause %1$s severe scalding. A remedy is a faucet with integrated mixed water shut-off and safety lock. You can also lower the heating temperature of your hot water boiler to prevent severe scalding.";
"danger_boiler_title" = "Ensure clean drinking water";
"danger_boiler_text" = "If you lower the heating temperature to avoid scalding, this can lead to the formation of bacteria such as legionella, which can harm you and your family. Old pipes can contaminate the drinking water. You can check the quality of your drinking water by regular water tests.";
"danger_cleaning_supplies_title" = "Safely lock chemicals";
"danger_cleaning_supplies_text" = "Detergents, cleaning products, and cosmetics contain chemicals that are lethal or dangerous for %1$s, especially if they get into the eyes or mouth. Sometimes the containers have a safety cap, but it is better to store them out of reach of the little ones. If this is not possible, you can also lock the cabinets with a magnetic lock.";
"danger_sofa_title" = "Prevent sofa / bed fall";
"danger_sofa_text" = "To prevent %1$s from injuring themselves by falling off the bed or sofa, you should not leave %1$s unattended. To prevent %1$s from falling off the bed, you can use a height-adjustable bed rail. However, keep in mind that older children often crawl over the rail as well, increasing the height at which they fall and the risk of injury. So use bed rails sensibly and at your own discretion.";
"danger_oven_title" = "Secure stove";
"danger_oven_text" = "On the hot stove top, %1$s can burn themselves very quickly and they can even get a hold of the handle of a cooking pot. There is a risk of severe scalding with hot contents. To prevent this, a safety grid for the stove can be helpful. If you don't want to use a grid, try to always turn the handle of your pots and pans backwards out of reach.";
"danger_ovenswitch_title" = "Secure stove knobs";
"danger_ovenswitch_text" = "The little kitchen helpers like to play with the knobs on the stove. But if the hotplate is turned on unnoticed, the entire kitchen can quickly catch fire. The appropriate fuses can prevent %1$s from turning it.";
"danger_ropes_title" = "Remove curtain cords and other ropes";
"danger_ropes_text" = "Ropes, cords, chains, cables but also curtains longer than 22cm are a danger for %1$s. The little ones like to wrap these things around their head or neck and can strangle themselves. Therefore, make sure to secure these things well in your home.";
"danger_candle_title" = "Avoid candles and scented oils";
"danger_candle_text" = "Candles and fire are, of course, always dangerous. Since %1$s can get burned by them, you should keep them out of reach. You should always use candles and scented oils around babies with caution, because their little noses are very sensitive. A safer alternative could be organic oils or an organic room spray instead.";
"danger_hair_title" = "Avoid Tourniquet Syndrome";
"danger_hair_text" = "Long hairs can wrap around your baby's fingers or toes and cut off the blood supply, causing fingers or toes to die. In technical terms, this is called Tourniquet syndrome. Keep checking your baby's fingers and toes.";
"danger_railing_title" = "Secure railing with bars with plexiglass";
"danger_railing_text" = "When using a grille or railing, make sure that the bars are no more than 65 mm apart. This way you can be sure that your child's head will not get stuck and %1$s will not suffocate. You can use plexiglass if the distance is greater.";
"danger_dishwasher_title" = "Secure dishwasher";
"danger_dishwasher_text" = "Little kitchen helpers can get scalded by hot steam when the dishwasher door is opened. If your dishwasher doesn't have an automatic shut-off, the hot water can also cause scalding. Here you can help with universal latches, so %1$s can not open the dishwasher so easily.";
"danger_cable_title" = "Cable out of range";
"danger_cable_text" = "The little explorers of the world like to put everything in their mouths and chew on it - especially when they are teething. Even cables are not safe from their mouths. These are not only dangerous because the little ones can strangle themselves with them - when chewing on a cable, %1$s can even suffer a fatal electric shock. Cable hoses can help keep the cables safely wrapped.";
"danger_pool_title" = "Secure pool and paddling pool";
"danger_pool_text" = "Pools and wading pools are particularly dangerous for little non-swimmers. Small children can drown in water that is only a few centimeters deep. Therefore, make sure that pools and paddling pools are inaccessible for %1$s.";
"danger_knife_title" = "Clear away sharp and pointed objects";
"danger_knife_text" = "%1$s can naturally hurt themselves with sharp and pointed objects if they handle them without your supervision. Therefore, do not leave knives, forks, scissors, tools and other sharp or pointed objects in your home, keep them out of reach.";
"danger_bag_title" = "Plastic bags out of reach";
"danger_bag_text" = "Plastic bags are not only harmful to our environment, but can also be dangerous to our young children. If %1$s put a plastic bag over their head, they could easily suffocate. Therefore, keep plastic bags out of reach or use cloth bags instead.";
"danger_toy_title" = "Check toys for harmful substances";
"danger_toy_text" = "Yes, even children's toys can be dangerous for %1$s. On one hand, they may not be suitable for the age of your child, and on the other hand, they can contain dangerous pollutants and plasticizers that are dangerous for %1$s in the long term. So when buying toys, look carefully at what materials the toy is made of and try to choose toys with natural materials.";
"danger_smallitems_title" = "Store small parts out of reach";
"danger_smallitems_text" = "The little world explorers first check their surroundings with their mouths, so anything they find goes right there first. If %1$s swallows the objects, the worst case is that the item clogs the airways and %1$s chokes on it. In the best case, the object comes to light again after some time, but it can still cause some damage in the body. Therefore, try to keep all small, round objects out of reach from your toddler.";
"danger_weapons_title" = "Lock weapons";
"danger_weapons_text" = "It is undisputed that weapons are not for children. Lock up firearms and stabbing weapons, but also batons and the like from your toddler. After all, you don't want %1$s to play with them and hurt or even kill themselves or others.";
"danger_battery_title" = "Batteries out of range";
"danger_battery_text" = "Batteries, especially button batteries, should be kept safe from your child. If %1$s swallows them, it's an emergency and you need to go to the hospital immediately. Button cells can cause serious damage to your child's esophagus.";
"danger_cutlery_title" = "Use children's cutlery";
"danger_cutlery_text" = "Knives, forks, scissors, flames, have no place in children's games! - so says the old proverb. The danger with cutlery is mainly the tips of the fork but sharp knives can also hurt %1$s. Of course, even the youngest children like to use cutlery like the grown-ups. Therefore, special children's cutlery with rounded tips and blunt knives is suitable.";
"danger_cover_title" = "Create pad and blanket free sleeping environment";
"danger_cover_text" = "For babies, blankets and bolsters also pose some danger, as they cannot free themselves if the bolster and blanket lands on their face. So if %1$s is still very small, avoid cushions and blankets when sleeping and when %1$s is unattended.";
"danger_mirror_title" = "Protect mirrors and glass from breakage";
"danger_mirror_text" = "Mirrors or glass plates pose a great danger, especially if they break. So that %1$s doesn't get hurt by splinters, you can buy shatterproof mirrors. These are especially suitable for the children's room. If you want to be on the safe side, you can also cover existing mirrors or glass surfaces with a special film.";
"danger_fireplace_title" = "Secure fireplaces";
"danger_fireplace_text" = "To protect %1$s against burns from a chimney or other fireplace in your home, a grate is can be very helpful. Unfortunately, normal grates are not suitable for this purpose, as they are often made of wood or plastic. A heat resistant safety grate will protect little curious kids from dangerous burns from fireplaces.";



/* TIPS */


"tip_electricity_title" = "Warum sind Steckdosen gefährlich?";
"tip_electricity_text" = "Man würde doch nie auf die Idee kommen einem Baby Stricknadeln oder einen Schraubenzieher zum Spielen zu überlassen. Warum sind dann Steckdosen so gefährlich?\n\nDie kleinen Weltentdecker werden von Steckdosen magisch angezogen. Viele Steckdosen befinden sich genau in Augenhöhe der kleinen Krabbler und ihre kleinen Fingerchen passen perfekt in die Öffnung europäischer Steckdosen. Du denkst vielleicht, dass der Fehlerstrom-Schutzschalter (FI-Schalter) dazu da ist, uns vor tödlichen Stromschlägen zu schützen. Der Schutzschalter greift aber erst, wenn ein Mensch in den Stromkreis eingreift. Für die kleinen Krabbelmäuse ist das allerdings zu spät. Daher sichere deine Steckdosen im gesamten Wohnbereich mit Steckdosensicherungen. Diese bekommst du in jeder Drogerie, Heimwerker- oder Elektromarkt und natürlich auch online. (Unten findest du unsere Empfehlungen, für die wir eine kleine Provision bekommen und das Sparschwein unsere Krabbelmaus füttern.)\n\nSteckdosensicherungen gibt es zum Kleben oder auch zum Schrauben. Für häufig verwendete Steckdosen empfiehlt es sich die Variante mit den Schrauben zu verwenden, für alle anderen reicht die Klebeversion aber völlig aus.\n\nDu kannst nicht immer und überall die Steckdosen absichern. Und beim Besuch bei Freunden erstmal alle Steckdosen verkleben macht dich nicht gerade zum Lieblingsbesucher. Lerne deinem Kind daher schon frühzeitig, dass Steckdosen nicht zum Spielen geeignet sind.\n\nHat dein Kind trotz aller Vorsicht einen Stromschlag bekommen oder besteht der Verdacht, so solltest du umgehend ins Krankenhaus fahren. Die Symptome, welche durch elektrischen Strom ausgelöst werden können, reichen von Verbrennungen an den Ein- und Austrittstellen, über Schädigungen von Organen bis hin zu Herzrhythmusstörungen und im schlimmsten Fall zu Atemstillstand.\n\n\n\nUnsere Empfehlung:\n\nDa du neben Steckdosensicherungen auch Schubladenschlösser, Kantenschutz, Kippsicherungen und Türstopper brauchen kannst, empfehlen wir folgendes Starterkit mit 12x Steckdosenschutz, 12x Eckenschutz, 6x Schranksicherung, 4x Schrankschloss, 5x Klemmschutz, 4x Universal Sicherung.\n\nNatürlich kannst du auch nur Steckdosensicherungen bestellen. Bitte achte auch darauf, ob es sich um  EU-Stecker und oder nicht EU-Steckerdosen handelt. ";
